##"night watchman" in Wuhan under epidemic situation

Micro Signal, Peopleweekly

Feature description, portrait of the Times.

The spring light of February has shown some beautiful, but every night, the epidemic in Wuhan is still chilly, frost chill. Medical Staff Day and night to fight in the "epidemic" front, "home" residents or have fallen asleep, in the city's streets, there are a group of "night watchmen" in the cold wind. The Dawn is not far, but it will come. In the darkest hour before the Dawn, this quiet night, it is they who are guarding

Photo and caption by Chen Liang editor Fang Yingzhong, Zheng Jie

The spring light of February has shown some beautiful, but every night, the epidemic in Wuhan is still chilly, frost chill. Medical Staff Day and night to fight in the "epidemic" front, "home" residents or have fallen asleep, in the city's streets, there are a group of "night watchmen" in the cold wind. The Dawn is not far, but it will come. In the darkest hour before the Dawn, this quiet night, it is they who are guarding

This article first appeared in the 2020 issue of southern people's weekly

Photo and caption by Chen Liang editor Fang Yingzhong, Zheng Jie

The full text is about 2172 and takes about 5 minutes to peruse

Nie Heping, a disinfection worker

Nie Heping, 48, Cleans and disinfects the North Gate of the Wembley Arena's Shelter Hospital, Stadium Road.

"It feels like Wuhan is really sick and the whole city is too quiet. Wuhan restricted travel, every day to work, is the most happy, can go out for a walk. The most important thing in the face of the epidemic is to remain optimistic. I am still young and have strong resistance. I am not afraid!"Nie Heping said, "when the epidemic is over, I will have a good rest for two days and take my family to Wuhan for a good turn. I am too busy. "

EMT Wang Ke

Wang Ke is a member of the "pneumonia first aid" class at the Wuhan Emergency Center. He is in charge of 120 first aid from 4:30 pm to 8:30 am the next day.

"since the outbreak, the whole city streets a few people, every day in three towns in Wuhan busy pick up and send first-aid patients, the heart felt lost, " Wang said. "I have a unique sense of accomplishment when I work with a hypoglycemic patient and resuscitate them through first aid. Now I work with patients who have new pneumonia and, in addition to helping them breathe, I also need to do more psychological counseling to cheer them up! "

120 Dispatcher Chen Lei

In the wake of the outbreak, the workload at Wuhan's emergency services has increased dramatically. 120 Dispatcher Chen Lei works nonstop from 8 p.m. to 8 a.m.

"Every day, there's a big proportion of respiratory disease calls, and there's an increase in all kinds of serious emergency cases. Often meet to send the patient to be unable to enter a hospital normally, special period, ambulance needs to roll over a few hospitals. I'M GONNA get the intake to the hospital, and I'm GonNa admit the patient. Whenever a patient is admitted to the hospital, I am very happy,"Chen said, "when it's over, I'm going to get a good night's sleep. "

Hotel manager Liu Lei

After 90, Liu Lei was the head of the anti-epidemic team of Pudding Hotel, which was close to the hospital, and became the lodging place for the frontline medical staff of provincial maternal and Child Health Care Hospital, Army General Hospital and 672 hospital.

"One night, while I was eating instant noodles, a doctor brought me a steamed bread from the hospital, and without any message, I felt quite warm. On the Lantern Festival, they brought Tangyuan from the hospital to eat for us, saying we had worked hard. "

Lu Mengting, a convenience store employee

The convenience store stays open 24/7, and Lu, 28, works nights from 8 p.m. to 8 a.m. the next day. Parents and brother are in Xiaogan, she and her boyfriend in Wuhan.

"No matter what you do, you have to take responsibility. You worked the night shift before the epidemic. It's the same thing. Now we don't have stores around us, and it feels like you've kept your promise to your customers and kept the light on. "

Fruit and vegetable processing worker Wang Hua

During the outbreak, the workload of Wang Hua, a vegetable and fruit processing worker in Wuhan, suddenly increased, basically adding about four hours, the longest time from 11 am to 11 am the next day.

"We used to pack and sort more than 10,000 parcels by more than 20 of us. Now less people, more than a dozen people to share, so the pressure is also greater. Because the staff is insufficient, still need to carry on the work of sifting fruit. But we eat well here, better than at home."

Food delivery driver Liu Lang

Liu Lang, a native of Jingmen, Hubei Province, returned to Wuhan at the height of the epidemic to help the city.

"When I was at home, watching all the news reports, touching first-line medical stories, seeing a mayor working on the first-line and being infected, I was very moved. I had supplies at home, but because the hotels and shops in Wuhan were mostly closed, I was worried about what the residents in Wuhan were eating... I had nothing to do at home anyway, so I came to do it."

Master Shen, Pastry Chef for breakfast

During the outbreak, Shen was in charge of preparing three meals a day for the medical staff of the nearby Shelter Hospital and the Han medical team. He went to work at 3 a.m. and worked until 5 or 6 p.m.

Shen was an 18-year-old soldier during the Wenchuan County earthquake. Although he was not sent to help, he saw the news and news from the front every day and wanted to help. "What a former soldier feels at times like this is that he can not stay at home. He lies at home and sees the news and wants to come right over and see what he can do to help. "

Delivery boy Zhang Cheng

Zhang Cheng did a rider without his mother's knowledge, during the epidemic, daily orders can reach 80-90 single, send single results in the top three regions. To facilitate his work, he used to cook five or six boiled eggs a day. Now he has to eat ten.

"My sense of achievement is the strongest. I delivered supplies to the Jiangsu medical team the other day. I was the only one who got the list, so I thought it would be glorious to give something to these retrograde angels in White. "

Liu Sheng, traffic police, Yangtze River Bridge

Liu Sheng, a 38-year-old deputy commander of the first squadron of the Yangtze River Bridge Traffic Police Brigade, returned to Hainan with his wife and 6-year-old child for the Lunar New Year before the outbreak. He had planned to go to Hainan on the day of the closure of the city to reunite with his family.

"there used to be so many cars on the Yangtze River bridge that you had to use odd and even numbers, and so many pedestrians and tourists every day. Now there are almost no cars and no people. During the outbreak, an old man walked from Hankou to Wuchang to deliver supplies to his daughter. He was exhausted after walking to the Yangtze River Bridge. When I found out, I helped him deliver it. The traffic disruption in the closed city of Wuhan has indeed caused great difficulties for everyone to travel,"Liu said, "The service is completely different now, 24 hours a day. After the epidemic is over, I'm going to invite the whole squadron to have a barbecue. It's too hard for everyone. "

Snow Man Chen Jianguo

February 15, Wuhan cliff-style Cooling, heavy wind and snow. South Central Wuchang Cleaning Team Chen Jianguo is in charge of the August 1 St Snowmelt. During the outbreak, he worked from 8 pm to 8 am the next day, disinfecting and cleaning the area in charge.

"Even though it is night time and Wuhan is always busy with traffic, now no one is to be seen, I feel very proud when I do disinfection outside the Wembley Arena's shelter every day, and I can do my bit to prevent and fight the epidemic. "

Didi driver Hu Jianbin

After the city, Didi team captain launched the recruitment of "medical protection team" , Free Transport Wuhan medical workers, Hu Jianbin the first application.

"At such a moment, being a Wuhan person is instinctive and necessary, " Hu said. "I had planned to take a road trip to Tibet with my wife. I hope it will happen as soon as the epidemic is over. "

Community Security Guard Ge Fei

Liu Yongjia in the Xiaogan countryside, January 23 closed the day back to Wuhan on duty, has been working for more than 20 consecutive days, more than 12 hours a day on guard duty. He was worried about the safety of his two children and looked forward to returning home when the epidemic was over.

"The situation in our community is well under control, and the owners are very understanding and supportive of us. We were also given three packs of masks by the owners on their own initiative, which is really touching. "
